segments.text: Well, Jerry, you came by the house here to get a little information about the history of College Station.
To begin with, I might add that my name is DA Andy Anderson, who at one time was, or I was, mayor of the city of College Station.
Actually, my work as
in the field of city government began in 1957.
Actually, I might go back just a little ways, though, first and mention that I came to this community in 1939.
At that time, prior to that time, I was located in Luskin, working for the university at that point.
with the Texas Forest Service.
And in January of this year, I retired from the university after about 39 years of employment.
Prior to that, I was affiliated with the US Forest Service and was involved during the acquisition phases of the National Forest in East Texas.
And my work prior to that was with the old Bureau of Plant Industry in white pine blister rust control activities.
Was that with the university?
No.
That was with the government?
No, that was with the federal government.
That was the Bureau of Plant Industry.
It was an old division of the U.S. Department of Agriculture from Washington, D.C.
Of course, my education, as far as my education is concerned, I got a bachelor of science degree at Pennsylvania State University.
I subsequently received a master's degree at Texas A&M.
And what year was that?
The master's I got in 19, I think it was 45.
I believe that was a year.
I'm reminiscing here a little bit now.
And I did a little work toward a doctorate degree, but decided that with the field activities that I had, I could not do justice to that degree program.
At any rate, my interest in city government began in the 50s when there was quite a bit of violation of the deed restrictions in College Station.
And I might add that when I first came here in 1939, Bryan and College Station were six miles apart.
It was a two-lane road with country in between, you might say.
Was that road the old College over here, College Road?
Well, there was a College Road, but also Highway 6.
I see.
Highway 6 had gone through.
Highway 6 had gone through.
just before I got here, and of course I came right after the trolley gave up from Bryan to College Station.
And this was a university community.
Everyone, well at that time, most of the faculty and staff were on campus, or quite a few of them were on campus, in residences on the campus.
Many, of course, had migrated to the periphery of the area, the campus per se,
And this house right here, where you're taping this, where I live, was one of the few that was in this whole area that we today call College Hills State, or the College Hills proper.
Where most of the faculty, you said, lived on the campus.
Now, did they move off over to this area as a group?
Most of them, or did they move off at separate times?
Was there a general move off?
Well, there was a general move here, Jerry.
They wanted to, well, they had requested that as fast as possible, those on the campus move from their residences.
many of these people began to build their own homes, such as in the South Side and the East Gate here.
So gradually, then, people began to build their homes and move into them and get off the campus.
About what year was this?
Was it 1940?
That was around 1939, 1940.
And gradually the area became built up with a few more homes going in.
And with the building of these homes, the individuals, the real estate people that were selling the lots, of course gave us some restrictions.
In other words, the homes were to be one family dwellings and
The sides on both residences were to be at least a minimum of 10 feet.
Was it kind of like a certain zoning?
It was like a type of zoning.
That is right.
But then as more interest, or there was greater interest in terms of home building, why those in charge of the railers and so on selling these lots became a little bit careless.
And as a result, there were a lot of violations.
And these violations led to criticisms on the part of the public.
And I just happened to be one that they came to.
It was my job to appeal to the council at that time as to these violations that were going on and appealing to the city to help us do something about it.
Well, how did you get, why were you sort of the one singled out to people?
Why did people come to you?
Well, I guess maybe I was one that didn't fear to go to the council and raise cane and see that action was done.
And this ultimately led, of course, to my election then.
to the city council.
The people over here in College Hill said, well, we need a representation at the council table who will represent us, the people.
And as a consequence, then, I went in in 1957.
And until it was necessary for me to get out in June of 1971,
I almost had, you might say, 14 years of continuous service to the city.
Well, now before that time, you got into the council.
When did College Station incorporate as a town or city separately from Bryan?
That was in 1938.
I see.
Yeah.
What were the reasons that they did that?
Were they afraid that Bryan was going to try to move their city?
No, we were unincorporated at that time, Jerry.
Okay.
And this is where a lot of the hard feelings arose that persist to this day.
Even the student body is unaware of the problems they had with the city of Bryan, I mean, in the past.
But we were an unincorporated city, you might say, made up primarily of students, faculty, and staff.
In that day, of course, there were no cars on campus, as you find today.
And it was mainly, it was the core.
Well, just what exactly was the school like?
How large was it at that time?
Were there a lot of buildings that are now on campus still there?
So let's go back to about when they were just talking about the incorporation of College Station and the reason why they had to do it, because Brian was trying to stretch there.
Yes.
Well, as I said before the interruption on the tape, Jerry, we were an unincorporated city.
Bryan was incorporated.
And one night, while at a special council meeting in Bryan, they decided to extend their boundary outward toward the city of College Station, or unincorporated city.
And as I said earlier, before the break, much of that area that is now in Brine, out here at Rosemary, was at one time a part of our College Station community.
This, of course, created a lot of blood between the people, the business people, and other people in Brine and College Station.
As a matter of fact, this bad blood even existed among the student body
a few years later when they banned everything in the city of Bryan.
They had sort of a revolt with the people down there with the treatment they were receiving.
But at any rate,
It became necessary for us then to meet and take immediate steps to incorporate our city.
Now this was before the days of zoning, which we now have by legislation.
And they could extend their boundary out as far as they wanted to.
Subsequent to that, then after we became incorporated, I was on the council.
We also received wind.
that they had intended to further extend their boundary to include the present airport.
So we immediately met... What was this airport?
Is this Easterwood?
Easterwood.
And we immediately met then and incorporated all the lands of Texas A&M University within the jurisdiction of our boundary so that today
All of the area encompassed within the city is represented by university lands.
I see.
Now, today we have the protection of zoning in terms of extraterritorial rights and extending out.
Brine can't exceed us in extending their territory.
We can only go one mile as a city.
But be that as it may, we have stabilized our boundary with brine.
Unfortunately, part of what is brine should have been part of College Station had the ordinances existing today
been in vogue at that time.
Now, you said the lands incorporated by the university lands, owned lands, were incorporated into the College Station City area?
That's right.
As part of the city.
Now, does that include the lands going out toward the Brazos where the extension formed?
No, no.
That just includes these lands here in town?
Yeah, in the immediate area.
That's right.
And Easterwood.
And Easterwood, yeah.
And we did that, of course, for our own protection because the city of Bryan at that time could just keep on going.

surround us and of course we wanted in defense we had to prepare a buffer and the community as a whole and the student body all was behind us in our record because of the feeling that existed at that time.
Well in talking about the student body I was just curious to how much effect or pressure did they have really on the
College Station City Councilman or the government in helping them or... Well, it was more in terms of attitude, Jerry, as to what we were doing.
The people of Bryan at one time, some of these students say, were gouging them.
They welcomed them to get what they could out of them.
But beyond that, they just didn't want to have anything to do with it.
And this created hard feelings on the part of the student body.
And...
Well, at the time of College Station becoming incorporated, the students at the university, were they, I guess they were for the incorporation of the city at this time?
Well, I would dare say they were.
Now, all of the faculty and staff were.
And the student body was to the extent that they didn't have much feeling for Brian.
Of course, you can go back.
In that early period, though, of course, A&M, for example, had various facilities on campus for students and faculty and staff.
For example, we had a hardware store over just across from where the President Exchange Store is.
And we could go in there and get anything.
We bought our milk and butter.
in our fruit and everything from the old F&B.
I recall paying $0.09 to $0.10 for a quart of milk.
It was unpasteurized, but it was high quality milk.
And of course, here again, the folks in Brine resented us getting anything of this nature from the university.
Well, what's the old F&B?
What was that?
Well, let's see.
I forgot what F&B was.
That's just what everybody called it.
Well, it was a name to it.
It was across the track, and it was a dairy.
Well, now, was that university-owned also?
Yes.
And all the stores, they liked to buy a few groceries of that sort.
They were all located either on campus or... Well, most of them were off campus.
Off campus.
Like, I recall Luke Patronella had a grocery store at the East Gate, and he was a well-respected man in the community, and...
Every year had Easter egg hunts for all the kids in the community.
Well, now, what about over at Northgate now?
Was that an area the same as it is now?
Has it always been sort of...
Somewhat similar to what it is now.
That is right.
There were just a few businesses up and down the drag there.
Now, of course, you have more today than you did at that time.
But essentially, it remained...
the same.
I mean, there was a grocery store and a few photographic shops, things of this nature.
Well, was Lupo there at that time or not?
Lupo has been around, yeah.
He was there.
He wasn't in that location.
He was further east on University Drive.
But Lupo was there when
I can remember him very fondly.
Well, how far now to the south did the College Station city boundaries go when y'all incorporated, to say toward Navasota that way?
Well, Jerry, they didn't go very far south out of the city at that time.
As a matter of fact, they didn't go very much beyond the south gate, just a peripheral area where the people were building.
So there wasn't any buildings going on then over that part of the... No, no.
At that time.
This came subsequent to this with the growth in the university.
You know, right down here we used to have, at the Eastgate, we used to have the old...
I know the old-time Aggies will remember the blue tops.
These were a series of cottages that were down there.
Any visitors to College Station...
you know, the parents and so on would stay in these old blue top courts down there.
And they have long since disappeared and their place taken by the lot down there and everything else.
Well, around 1940 or so, 1939, how large was the university at that time, the student body?
It was around 5,000, I believe.
I reckon it would be there.
During the war, what kind of effect did, say, the war have on the growth and the economy of this area?
Do you remember?
Yes.
It had an effect.
Of course, the student body, of course, we had Brian Field come in.
That helped very much the economy of the area.
And actually that was the first base also after they left for transportation by plane into the Bryan and College Station area.
But the student body increased some because of the war effort.
Of course it had other, I don't think the, in terms of growth in the community, I don't think there was much
much effect at all, right?
No, except for homes of those out in Bryan Field, and most of them lived in Bryan.
Some lived in this area.
I know during that period, I was on two assignments for the Army and Navy.
One had to do, as a university employee, I was charged to look for Waiuli in the Trans-Pecos region.
They were running short of rubber.
And the Waiuli, of course, produces natural rubber.
And I spent three months on that assignment.
And following that, then the Navy put me out on a special assignment, confidential in nature.
They were running short of hemp rope.
And I had to go out to
check the Trans-Pacific or the western part of the state in terms of yucca to see how much rope could be made from the yucca if it were utilized.
Of course, this took me all down into old Mexico, and I went down through that country.
I've been all through that.
I know that country pretty intimately, or at least I did.
I was down there on at least two assignments during the war.
Of course, they were short, but very interesting trips.
Well, who was the mayor of College Station when it first became corporate?
When was their mayor?
Let's see.
Frank Anderson was the mayor.
He was then succeeded by Ernest Lankford, who served most of the time as mayor.
Well, he served up until the time that I took over in 1957.
And I served six years as councilman under him before I ran for mayor.
And at the time, I was petitioned by a large number of citizens to run, and I did.
And I served almost six years until the suit was brought against me.
And I know it was primarily against me
an individual at the East Gate whom we all know as AP Boyette.
He and some other individuals filed suit against the city of College Station.
Well, not the city.
Well, yes, it included the city, but primarily included us as individuals, saying that even though we did not receive any salary, no remuneration whatever,
that it was illegal for us to serve as an officer of the city while we were a member of the university.
And of course, this went to court.
It went to several courts, as a matter of fact.
And then finally, it was decided in one district court that that was the law of the land.
It was subsequently taken to a three
manned judge panel in Houston.
But before they could act, the Supreme Court turned that action down.
That necessitated then the development of an amendment to the state constitution that would allow us to continue to serve.
And I took the leadership in this.
It was called Amendment 12.
And all my correspondence, legal papers, things of this nature, now repose in the library, permanent part of the library, so that in the future,
The history of this can be eternal.
Well, at what time now was this action going on?
You said you served six years as mayor starting in 1957?
Well, starting in 57, I served six years on the city council.
I see.
And then I decided to get out, and when I did get out, they asked me to go back and serve on planning and zoning.
And then following my tenure on that, they decided that the best thing to do was run for mayor.
And then I ran for mayor after that and was mayor from 66 through June 28 in 1971.
When, following the holding up of four paychecks, it was decided that principal had gone far enough.
I just couldn't live without the salary.
Right.
I see.
But I am very pleased with the...
period of my tenure and those on the council.
We had an excellent council at the time of my retirement and even before that.
Of course we had a lot of problems when I first went on the city council because it was dominated by AP Boyette primarily and his group.
They were in the majority and I was trying to get development in the city.
in cooperation with the university.
What we see today is a result of action that we had earlier taken.
But we had a council jury made up, for example, of the system dean of engineering.
We had one from sociology department.
We had one from planning department.
We had a cross-section of individuals on the council that was really working
on behalf of the city.
And what we were doing, of course, was in favor of the university in the sense that we had a coordinated approach in terms of development.
Well, what kind of development was the council, when you were on it or when you were mayor at the time, trying to go toward?
What were they looking for?
Well, when I went in as mayor,
We had a few streetlights in the city of College Station.
What now is Jersey Street was just Tar Bay Street for two vehicles.
We did not have what we now know as University Drive.
There were no, well the city had been small.
Our staff was small.
We needed to expand the staff.
We needed to improve the services in terms of fire codes, building codes.
We had no fire station.
The university provided the firefighting for the city of College Station.
Our water, of course, came primarily at first from the university.
and then subsequently from Brine.
We have tie-ins, of course, with the university.
But in that period, it was one, or had to be one, of growth.
And the extension of the Highway 6 towards the south was undertaken even before the council on which I served went on.
We had University, or I mean Jersey Drive,
I was criticized to some extent for, at that time, well, they figured, well, we only needed two slabs, you know, for two cars.
But it appears now that our foresight was justified when you consider the traffic that is over there.
That's true.
And the same thing was said with University Drive, extending it out to the Interpass.
We did fight very hard to get the east bypass.
I was going to ask about that.
I was wondering when did that come into, when did that idea pop up?
Was that organized mostly by the state then?
Is that a state highway?
No, that was Brazos Area Planning Corporation, on which I served as member.
And we had a plan developed for Bryan and College Station way back in,
That was about 49, as I recall.
And this was the guiding light for the two cities in terms of plans.
And that was the first time that the possibility of a bypass came up, looking toward the future.
Now, in that period even, Highway 6 did not have the travel, you know, traffic that it does today.
But we as a council, of course, pushed this, recognizing the need down the road.
And I think we have been justified in our vision to this extent.
And of course, we were beset with problems.
We were a city on a pay-as-you-go basis.
I think we had one of the best road construction programs.
We had no pay streets in the city of College Station.
And we decided to set aside a certain amount of money annually for curb and gutter pavement.
And that was set up on a ratio whereby people could petition and get streets in.
But we did not do any more in a given year than our finances permitted.
And this way, we just kept growing year after year.
That is, in the old part of the city, in order to do this.
And then, of course, we went ahead with our street light program, at least on major intersections.
And these green, well, years ago, we started out with little corner stops with a street name written on them.
You've seen some still in parts of the city.
And if you drive around in the daytime or at night, you do not know what the name of the street is.
So we have these green signs prepared for street designations.
Now, we had our park areas.
We had one like up here in College Hill that sat dormant for years.
To this end, for example, I instituted a planning program down at our cemetery where we grew trees and out planted them in the park areas.
Many of the trees that you see today are a result of this particular action.
And I was one that very much believed in community participation.

And toward this end, I had many committees in the city, even a cemetery committee, one that would take care of the cemetery and, you know, see that the rules and regulations were upheld and highway improvements.
Just any number of city committees.
Well, what kind of regulations and rules did you have to go along with on the cemetery committee?
What type of things did they have to do?
Well, what we were trying to avoid, Jerry, was the idea to regulate the size of a monument and even the planting of trees.
Now, I realize that people do not realize that there are some, at the time at least, tend to
plant trees that are not conducive to a cemetery create problems in terms of growth, not only from the top and leaf litter, but from the extension of roots.
And many of the trees in an old cemetery utilize this area, why the roots are broken and the trees finally succumb.
And we were trying to maintain a pretty place
and regulate the outplanting of shrubs and flowers and things that would not fit into the overall scheme.
And we didn't want one to put out a massive stone and another one would be a small one.
Regulations of this type.
I see.
I think we're about out of tape here.
I'll switch it over.
All right.
